The rejuvenation under the great leader.
London – The Battle of Waterloo is now 200 years in the past, a catastrophic defeat for Napoleon that badly damaged French self-esteem to such an extent that General Charles de Gaulle omitted it from his writings on French military history.
Nevertheless, if you acknowledge that “greatness” is a matter of personal traits, then both Napoleon and de Gaulle could be considered the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would say that there is no such thing as a great leader.
According to Marx, the class struggles in France created an environment where_chars like Napoleon, described as "奇异的庸才" (奇异 means "strange" or "peculiar," and 庸才 means "ordinary talent" or "mediocre talent"), became heroes.
According to Tolstoy, Napoleon was not an especially outstanding general, and his victories should be attributed to the courage and dedication of the French soldiers who won the Battle of Borodino.
Whether Napoleon was great or not, we must clarify whether greatness can be applied to any leader.
If the answer is affirmative, then who can be described as great?
Political philosopher Isaiah Berlin believed that great leaders must meet two particularly important criteria.
Firstly, can this leader recognize the historical trends?
Otto von Bismarck did so, as did his German compatriot Konrad Adenauer; both, in Bismarck’s unforgettable formulation, heard the “rustling of the Almighty’s cloak.”
Secondly, did this leader make any important decisions?
Of course, if leaders are forced to make decisions, they should not be blamed for them any more than they should be credited for them.
Therefore, the key lies in whether leaders have the opportunity to weigh pros and cons and make the right decisions on behalf of the country.
De Gaulle should therefore be listed among any great leader's ranks.
Almost单凭一己之力, he led France out of the post-World War II economic doldrums.
After regaining power in 1958, he again saved his country, suppressing two attempted coups, ending the Algerian War, and instituting the constitution of the Fifth Republic.
Similar to British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, Charles de Gaulle gave the French a new worldview that secured their place in the postwar global order.
In fact, the ultimate impact of de Gaulle and Churchill in establishing their respective national worldviews was perhaps overstated.
Their successors continue to view the world—and the role their country plays in it—through the lens of constraining rationality and distorting decision-making many years later.
The result is that the leaders of the two countries have since failed to achieve anything that can compare with the accomplishments of these two great leaders.
But there is one British prime minister who can match her in this regard: Margaret Thatcher, a highly controversial figure whom people either love or hate just as much.
Even her resignation 25 years ago was rooted in opposition activities within her own cabinet and party.
But you don't need to please everyone to become a great leader.
In fact, even Thatcher's critics cannot deny her impact.
Apart from being the first female prime minister of the United Kingdom and nearly the earliest in many other countries around the world to have a female prime minister, Thatcher helped to turn around the UK's economic decline.
Moreover, its attack on too-powerful unions gained manageability at a moment when the country seemed to be sliding into turbulence and chaos.
Given this, she undoubtedly has the right to be a candidate for the "Great Leader."
Similarly, although far from infallible, Deng Xiaoping in China also qualifies as a great leader.
In addition to assisting Mao Zedong in doing evil, Deng also played a decisive role in ordering the Tiananmen Square massacre in 1989.
But Deng simultaneously invigorated the market, setting China on a path of unprecedented development and prosperity that eventually lifted billions of Chinese out of poverty.
Many people regard Singapore's founding father and longtime prime minister Lee Kuan Yew as a great figure, although he may have wished for a larger stage to showcase his talents.
In fact, the size of a country seems to have no impact on one becoming a great leader.
When I said that a small country like Luxembourg is unlikely to produce great leaders, I had no insult intended, especially given that the country's political atmosphere is generally not controversial.
The United States is vast enough to be the birthplace of great leaders.
Some presidents have indeed achieved a great deal.
Harry Truman and Dwight Eisenhower — while not thinkers of巨人的magnitude — nevertheless demonstrated卓越的判断力statesman-like judgment in establishing the post-war international order that would支撑世界和平sustain peace for several decades.
Others, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, possessed a high degree of charisma — the art of stirring and persuading.
John F. Kennedy could be said to have had strengths in many areas.
He accomplished a great task: defusing the Cuban Missile Crisis.
His inspirational talent was unparalleled; in fact, his assassination after death only reinforced the traditions he had left behind.
In South Africa, there has been no one else who can be considered a great figure since Nelson Mandela's death; Mandela embodied courage, authority, and generous grandeur.
In fact, he was the most charismatic leader I have ever met; the other two – former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former US Secretary of State Colin Powell – are either African or African American.
So today?
The only one entitled to call itself great is the de facto leader of the European Union, German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Like former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she is often underestimated at the start, but rarely makes wrong decisions when it comes to making important ones.
Kohl established generous terms for German unification; Merkel opposed Putin when he invaded Ukraine and took a tolerant stance on the migrant crisis.
I think Marx and Tolstoy were wrong.
Political leaders, who wield political power, can shift the tide—for better or for worse.
Angela Merkel is the most prominent example today, as she has pointed the way for Europe to confront its high-stakes survival crisis.
